In Kubernetes, YAML files tell the cluster what you want.

Every YAML mainly has 3 parts:

1. Metadata (identity): This tells who the resource is.
âžœ name
âžœ namespace
âžœ labels (used to group and select resources)

2. Spec (desired state): This tells what you want Kubernetes to do.
âžœ  how many pods
âžœ which image
âžœ ports, env vars, volumes

3. Status (actual state): This is written by Kubernetes, not you.
âžœ Is the pod running or failed?
âžœHow many replicas are ready?

